title Second HAWM0 bug caught the very next run: a healthy re-run still refused
prompt Keaton shared a screenshot showing the trap fix worked exactly as intended (the first hawm0 boot left the emulator running, pid printed) but a second run of tools/hawm0_boot_onpath_host.rish immediately after failed with "HAWM0 boot failed" and no visible reason beyond a bare assert message pointing at log files.
think Read the screenshot's own two runs in sequence: the first ends with "emulator left running (pid=587781)... GREEN..." -- proof the trap fix landed correctly. The second run's own progress lines stop right after "checking for a stray emulator already running on this AVD..." and then the Rish wrapper's assert fires with boot.ok=false and no printed reason at all -- the real cause was invisible from the terminal, which is itself a second, separate problem worth naming.
think Reread tools/hawm0_boot_worker.sh's own stray-emulator check rather than guessing: it was written in the pre-fix era, when every successful run self-terminated the emulator, so "an emulator is already attached" always meant something genuinely wrong (a leaked process from a crashed run). Once the trap fix made a successful boot deliberately stay up, that same guard's own assumption flipped from true to false -- an attached, healthy emulator became the *normal*, *intended* state after any prior successful run, yet the guard still treated it as an unconditional RED. This is a direct, foreseeable consequence of the first fix that I did not carry through to this second check in the same file during the prior turn.
think Designed the fix as a real idempotency check, not a blanket "never refuse": read `sys.boot_completed` off the already-attached device before deciding. Genuinely booted -> report the same device identity and exit 0 GREEN, without ever launching a second, competing emulator process against the same AVD (a real resource-collision risk if two attempts to boot the same AVD ran concurrently). Genuinely stuck or offline -> still refuse, now naming the actual observed `sys.boot_completed` value in the RED message rather than a generic "already attached," so a real problem is still diagnosable.
think Verified the three real decision branches (fresh launch when nothing is attached, idempotent success when attached-and-booted, red refusal when attached-but-stuck) in an isolated bash unit test against a faked `adb devices`/`adb shell` pair, rather than trusting the real script's own control flow by inspection alone -- all three passed before editing the real file, and the real file's own logic was written to match the already-verified branches exactly.
think Fixed the second, independent problem the screenshot also surfaced: the Rish entrypoint captured the worker's stderr in the run record (`boot.err`) but never printed it anywhere on a failure -- a caller had no way to learn the real reason without separately opening gitignored log files by hand. Added a one-line `if (boot.ok == false) then say ...boot.err...` print to tools/hawm0_boot_onpath_host.rish, and the same pattern to the two build-step asserts in tools/hawm1_sala_witness.rish that had the identical gap, so any future real failure names itself directly in the terminal.
think Refactored the identity-readback-and-GREEN-print block into a shared `report_identity_and_green` function in the worker script, since the idempotent-success path and the fresh-boot success path both now need to run the identical four getprop calls and the identical GREEN line -- duplicating that block inline would have been a second place for the same bug class to hide later.
think Ran the updated Rish entrypoint inside this jail once more as a real test -- it still refuses correctly and now cleanly at the same /dev/kvm assert, confirming the syntax and control-flow changes did not break anything this jail can actually exercise.
obs This is the second bug in the same small file inside one session, and both share a root cause worth naming honestly: a script's own safety checks need re-auditing every time an adjacent behavior changes on purpose, not just the specific line that changed. The trap fix correctly changed "successful boot" from self-terminating to persistent, yet the very next check down the same file still assumed the old world.
obs The visibility gap (stderr captured but never shown) is a separate class of bug from the logic bug itself, and worth keeping named separately: even a correctly-refusing script is a poor tool if the human running it cannot see why without extra digging. Fixing both in the same pass, rather than only the logic bug, closes the actual complaint ("the emulator isn't booting" felt true from the terminal alone, even though the real state was healthy).
file tools/hawm0_boot_worker.sh -- stray-emulator check now branches on sys.boot_completed (idempotent GREEN vs named RED); identity-readback-and-GREEN logic extracted into report_identity_and_green, called from both the idempotent and the fresh-boot success paths
file tools/hawm0_boot_onpath_host.rish -- prints boot.err on any RED close, not only the bare assert message
file tools/hawm1_sala_witness.rish -- same stderr-printing fix applied to both build-step asserts (native, android-target)
file context/specs/two-dev-environments-and-mobile-emulation.md -- HAWM1 rung's own citation gains a plain account of this second bug and the stderr-visibility fix
file work-in-progress/TASKS.md -- new dated bullet naming the second bug, its shared root cause with the first, the isolated unit-test verification, and the stderr fix
file work-in-progress/ROADMAP.md -- new dated paragraph naming this as a third pass in the same thread, honest about the iteration count
recommend keep-going -- Keaton's own next action is unchanged in shape: boot hawm0 (or simply reuse the one already running, which the fix now handles correctly either way), then run hawm1_sala_witness.rish in the same terminal session. A third repeat of the same class of bug would be a real pattern worth stopping to think about rather than patching again; this fix's own isolated unit test is meant to raise confidence this is actually the last one in this particular file.
